body:
Yeah, sorry I meant CHECK().

I've narrowed it down and it's definitely the CHECK(nil != string). If I comment that out, it builds and links fine. Adding the explicit cast of nil does not make a difference.

Here's a full example that's similar to my test.

2 differences that I note from your test, I'm using MRC not ARC and my string is dynamically allocated (though I have no idea why that would matter).

TEST_CASE("test") {
@autoreleasepool {

SECTION("Section") {
NSString *string  = [[@"hello world" dataUsingEncoding:NSUTF8StringEncoding] base64EncodedStringWithOptions:0];
CHECK(nil != string);
}

}
}

I started playing with this and removing const from the reference arg allows the above CHECK() to link properly.

So:
std::string toString( NSString \* CATCH_ARC_STRONG & nsstring );

Thanks Phil, I'm on Xcode 8.2.1 now. My workaround was the same as above, I simple removed const from the toString() functions.

Edit: Unlike the original report, this is with ARC enabled.

Against 1.5.7
```
@@ -1594,7 +1594,7 @@ std::string toString( std::nullptr_t );
 
 #ifdef __OBJC__
     std::string toString( NSString const * const& nsstring );
-    std::string toString( NSString * CATCH_ARC_STRONG const& nsstring );
+    std::string toString( NSString * CATCH_ARC_STRONG & nsstring );
     std::string toString( NSObject* const& nsObject );
 #endif
 
@@ -8202,7 +8202,7 @@ std::string toString( std::nullptr_t ) {
             return "nil";
         return "@" + toString([nsstring UTF8String]);
     }
-    std::string toString( NSString * CATCH_ARC_STRONG const& nsstring ) {
+    std::string toString( NSString * CATCH_ARC_STRONG & nsstring ) {
         if( !nsstring )
             return "nil";
         return "@" + toString([nsstring UTF8String]);
